result.execSummary:
The defendant Emily J Jarvis was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (5th or 6th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Emily J Jarvis in court, in custody, with attorney Joseph J. Dorlack.   Debra Lynn Blasius appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Court orders the following: 
- Total sentence: 6 years (Initial Confinement: 3 years, Extended Supervision: 3 years)CONCURRENT to 14CF747.  STAYED.  Credit for 37 days if revoked.
- Defendant IS NOT eligible for Challenge Incarceration
- Defendant IS eligible for Substance Abuse Program
- 3 years Probation
- 36 months Drivers License Revocation. 
- 36 months Ignition Interlock on any vehicle TITLED OR REGISTERED to defendant 
- Alcohol Assessment
- There is $2,500.00 cash posted in 14CF747.  Poster to contact the court within 1 week to advise whether the money should be applied to fines and costs in this matter and in 14CF747 or if it should be refunded.
- Court costs of $268.00 to be paid as a Condition of Probation
- Blood Test Reimbursement of $35.00 paid through Waukesha County Circuit Court to be forwarded to Waukesha Police Department
- DNA Surcharge of $250.00 to be paid as a Condition of Probation
- Conditions of Probation:  Defendant not to drive a motor vehicle without a valid license.  Follow through with Mental Health treatment/counseling.  Valid prescriptions to be taken in the manner they were prescribed.  Defendant to obtain trauma informed care.  Submit to an AODA assessment and follow through with any treatment/counseling.  DNA Sample if not yet provided, defendant to pay surcharge.
CONDITION TIME: 6 months - NON WORKING HOURS WITH STANDARD RELEASE CONDITIONS - CONSECUTIVE to Condition Time in 14CF747.  All 6 months STAYED and defendant to be released to Day Report Center for compliance for 120 days.
